ile presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors, Frenchy18th centuryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAge of Enlightenment.  aAn Essay on Man.  aAnecdote.  aAtheism.  aBaron d'Holbach.  aBlaise Pascal.  aCandide.  aCartesianism.  aCauses of the French Revolution.  aChristianity.  aConfucius.  aConyers Middleton.  aCurate.  aDeism.  aDemocritus.  aDenis Diderot.  aDictionnaire philosophique.  aDieu.  aDoctor Akakia.  aEinhard.  aEnfer.  aEriphyle.  aErudition.  aFrederick the Great.  aFriedrich Nicolai.  aGeorge I of Great Britain.  aHabilitation.  aHorace Walpole.  aHudibras.  aIconoclasm.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJacques Necker.  aJansenism.  aJean Calas.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJean-Jacques.  aJohann Christoph Gottsched.  aJonathan Swift.  aLaurence Sterne.  aLiterature.  aLouis XV of France.  aLucretius.  aMachiavellianism.  aMadame de Pompadour.  aManichaeism.  aMark Twain.  aMaurice de Saxe.  aMelodrama.  aMemoir.  aMercure de France.  aMolière.  aMonsieur.  aMontesquieu.  aNeoclassicism.  aNewtonianism.  aOn the Universe.  aPangloss.  aParlement.  aParody.  aPatrician (ancient Rome).  aPersecution.  aPharsalia.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophes.  aPhilosophy.  aPhysiognomy.  aPicaresque novel.  aPoetry.  aPolitique.  aPope Benedict XIV.  aPrimitivism.  aProse.  aProtestantism.  aRidicule.  aRomanticism.  aSatire.  aScholasticism.  aSimplicissimus.  aSimplicius Simplicissimus.  aSo